{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_aetna_ver02/data/sn92060454/00393346759/1945080401/0130.xml":{"full_text":"Wi)t Union tEnne#\nOfficial Weekly Labor Organ Voicing The Interests Of The American Federation of Labor\nFIGHT\nth\u00ab\nMar MARKET!\nMB\nWE PLEDGE\n1 BULLION DOLLARS\nIN\nWAR SAVINGS BONDS\nVOT XT,-, 1 Entered as Second Class Matter May 5, 1941, at the Post Office\n1NO. 1J at \u00bbfew Haven, Conn., under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nNEW HAVEN, CONN., SATURDAY, AUGUST 4, 1945\nas^^B\u2018 i A.F.L. NEWS SERVICE PRICE 5 CENTS\nBritish Vote Cited At Tull Work\u2019 Hearing\nConn. Job Insurance Cuts Vacation Pay\nUnusual Ruling\nPrompts Appeal\nByGarmentUnion\nState Department Regards\nVacation Fund Benefits\nAs Compensation For\nLoss Of Wages\nApproximately 6,000 mem\nbers of the International\nLadies Garment Workers\nUnion and thousands of work\ners in other industries in Con\nnecticut are being deprived\nof unemployment benefits\nthrough an unusual interpre\ntation of the state\u2019s unemploy\nment compensation law which\nregards vacation fund benefits\nas compensation for loss of\nwages. The union made these\ncharged at hearings before the\nAssistant Attorney General of\nConnecticut held in Hartford.\nThe union was represented at\nthe hearings by Sam Janis,\n1LGWU organizer in the area, and\nby Grace Milgram, a member of\nthe union\u2019s Research Department.\nDIFFERENT IN OTHER STATES\nThey reported to Assistant At\ntorney General Harry Silverstone\nand officials of die Unemployment\nCompensation Commission of the\nConnecticut Department of Labor\non the union\u2019s experience with un\nemployment compensation systems\nin other states.\nThe provision of the law which\nis being interpreted in such a\nmanner as to deprive workers of\ntheir first week of unemployment\ncompensation reads: \u201cAn indi\nvidual shall be ineligible for bene\nfits during any week with re\nspect to which the individual has\nreceived or is about to receive re\nmuneration in the form of\nany payment of wages.\u201d\nWorkers who have received vaca\ntion fund checks as provided for in\nILGWU agreements are being told\nthat the period for which they are\neligible to receive unemployment\ncompensation will start one week\nlater than usual.\nThe union contends that its vaca\ntion benefits are not compensation for\nloss of wages, that in no other state\nwhere the ILGWU is organized has\nsuch an interpretation been placed\nupon the vacation-benefit terms of its\nagreements and that in theory it is\npossible for a member of the union,\nworking under terms of a contract\nproviding such benefits, to receive\nthem even during a year in which\nhe is employed 52 weeks.\nActing on the theory that the\nbenefit is compensation, the Con\nnecticut unemployment compensa\ntion authorities are allowing par\ntial compensation, representing the\namount of the difference between\nthe vacation benefit and the full\ntotal of unemployment benefit to\nwhich the worker is entitled on the\nbasis of his earnings.\nThis interpretation is being in\nvoked in cases involving dll crafts\nand branches of the women\u2019s gar\nment industry. All unions in Con\nnecticut which have written vaca\ntion benefits into their contracts\nare awaiting a decision on the argu\nments that have been presented\nby the ILGWU. 1\n$250,000 Back Pay\nWon By Teamsters\nLOS ANGELES, Calif.\u2014(FP)\nCalifornia truck drivers, members of\nInternational Brotherhood of Team\nsters, will receive more than $250,000\nin retroactive pay.\nJust approved by the National\nTrucking Commission is the Moto^\nTruck Association contract which\ngives drivers an increase of 5c per\nhour retroactive to Jan. 1, 1945, with\na mileage rate increase for long line\ndrivers of .002c per mile retroactive\nto April 3, 1945. Covered in the in\ncrease are Teamster locals in Los\nAngeles, Santa Maria, San Bernar\ndino, San Diego, Long Beach, El Cen\ntro, Santa Barbara and Bakersfield.\nBuilding Trades\nPraise Feinmark\nOn O\u2019 Toole Choice\nThe Board of Business Agents\nof the New Haven Building\nTrades Council, meeting at the\nNew Haven Labor Temple Mon\nday, unanimously voted to con\ngratulate Harold V. Feinmark,\nsecretary-treasurer of the Conn.\nFederation of Labdr, upon his\nselection of J. Lawrence O\u2019Toole,\nBridgeport Bricklayers, as Assis\ntant Secretary of the Federation.\nExpressing their pleasure at the\nchoice of a building tradesman,\nthe Board also went on record as\ncommending the appointment\nof O\u2019Toole to the post.\nThe Board also voted to in\nstruct Secretary Vincent J. Mc\nGovern, Electricians, B-90, to\ncongratulate Feinmark upon his\nrecovery from his recent illness.'\nJames DiLonardo, Bricklayers,\nis president.\nAs We See It\nby\nTHE STAFF\nWE ESPECIALLY call our\nreaders\u2019 attention to two items in\nthis week\u2019s issue. First is the re\nport on Page 1 of the hearing held\nin Washington pn the \u201cFull Em\nployment Bill,\u201d which is endorsed\nby the A.F.L. This bill, which\naffects every working man and his\nfamily, may be the answer to our\nfear that there will be 10,000,000\nunemployed after Japan is de\nfeated. Read the article, and be\nready to answer the labor-haters\nwho oppose it.\nSecondly, the editorial by Harry\nFeinmark on Page 4, provides, in\na few short paragraphs, the basic\nreasons why organized labor is\ncalling for the elimination of the\nLittle Steel formula. The editorial\nis \u201cmust\u201d reading for the unions\nnow involved in contract negotia\ntions.\n\nGOOD war news is bad stock\nmarket news. The IV. Y. Times\nfound that about 730,000 shares\nwere dumped on the market in the\nfinal sixty minutes of a recent day\non which rumors of Japanese peace\nwere circulated.\n\nAN advertisement in the Miami\n(Fla.) Herald recently;\nFREE RUM NO LIMIT\nAll you pay is the\nFederal tax _1..$1.53\nState tax _ .24\nFreight _ .05\nBottle, label and cap _ .05\nInsurance.. .02\nLabor, etc. 06\n(Fifth) $1.95\nRegular _ 4.11\n\nGREEDY landlords at summer\nresorts are raking in profits at a\nfabulous rate, with rents in many\nresort areas having risen 200 to\n300 per cent since 1943. Typical\nof the rent gouging now going on\n(Continued on Page Four)\nFaithful To Labor\nNELS J. NELSON\nis receiving slate-wide congratu\nlations upon completing a quar\nter of a century as treasurer of\nthe Bridgeport Carpenters Dis\ntrict Council. In the 25 years\nhe has held office, Nelson has al\nways been elected unanimously,\nand has the record of having\nmissed only three meetings in\nall that time. We sincerely con\ngratulate him!\nCity Employees\nMass Meeting\nAt Taft Aug. 13\nCitizens Advisory Board To\nGive Full Support To\nMunicipal Workers\nA preliminary meeting of the Citi\nzens Advisory Board of the New\nHaven Joint Council of Municipal\nEmployees, A.F.L., was held at the\nHotel Taft Monday evening, in prep\naration for the mass meeting of city\nworkers to be held there on August\n13. The meeting, which was highly\nsuccessful produced the following\nresults:\n1. It was clearly shown that the\ncitizens of New Haven, once they\nunderstand the aims and aspira\ntions of organized city employees,\nbelieve that the city government, as\nan employer representing the pub\nlic, will live up to the terms of the\nordinance unanimously passed by\nthe Board of Aldermen, which pro\nvides for real grievance machinery\nto settle any differences between\ncity department heads or boards,\nand organizations representing city\nemployees.\n2. It was agreed that the organ\nized city employees, including the\nNew Haven Teachers League, which\nis working closely with the A.F.L.\ncity workers unions, are as inter\nested in maintaining and extending\nthe standards of municipal service\nto the public as they are in correct\ning inequities in regards to wages\nand working conditions.\nThe meeting was presided over by\nWilliam Hartigan, chairman of the\nJoint Council, and member of Local\n825, New Haven Fire Fighters Asso\nciation. The chief addresses were\ngiven by Ellis Ranen, General Or\nganizer of the American Federation\nof State, County, and Municipal Em\nployees, A.F.L., with which the Fire\nFighters, Local 530, Policemen\u2019s\nUnion, and Local 287, Board of Edu\ncation Employees are affiliated; Miss\nAgnes Wallace, president of the New\nHaven Teachers League; and Harold\nV. Feinmark, secretary-treasurer of\nthe Conn. Federation or Labor.\nThe organizational meeting of the\nCitizens Advisory Board, it was de\ncided, will be held Thursday, August\n9, at 7:30 P. M. at the Chamber of\nCommerce office.\nOthers who spoke briefly were\nRev. Edward J. Shea, St. Berna\ndette\u2019s R. C. Church; Rev. Francis\nB. Barnett, All Saints Chapel;\nCharles J. Ducey; George Thorpe,\npresident of Conn. Council 16,\nState City A.F.L. Unions; and\nNathan Sherman. The Joint Coun\ncil of Municipal Employees was\nalso represented by its secretary,\nHarold Spang, Board of Education\nEmployees; its treasurer, George\nLawlor, who is president of the\n(Continued on Page Two)\nPoverty Seen As\nBasis Of Prejudice\nWASHINGTON (FP) Gov.\nEllis Arnall of Georgia, who is being\npushed in some quarrers as the \u201clib\neral Democratic spokesman of the\nnew south,\u201d writes in Colliers\u2019 that all\nof Dixie's ills, including the racial\nproblem, are a direct result of poverty.\n\u201cThe average American annual in\ncome at the time of Pearl Harbor was\n$604. In the south it was $314. The\naverage Negro income was consid\nerably lower. No plan to cure the\nsouth of its ills will succeed which\ndoes not make that differential its\nfirst order of business,\u201d Arnell de\nclared.\ni\n\u201cThe so-called race question is an\neconomic one, not social. Pay the\nNegro good wages for his work, give\nhim the opportunity to learn, work\nand earn, give him his constitutional\nrights, and you have solved this dis\ntorted so-called race problem. Only\nthe demagogue tries to make political\ncapital of social equality, of racial\nintermarriage.\u201d\nHancock Mutual\nGroup Goes A.F.L.\nWASHINGTON\u2014(FP)\u2014District\nagents and debit writers of the John\nHancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.\nin Illi\u00a3\u00a3)is voted in an NLRB election\n167 to 55 for the Industrial Ordi\nnancy Insurance Agents Union, AFL,\nover the United Office Professional\nWorkers, CIO. The NLRB certified\nthe AFL union.\nJ--\n\u201cA Cloud No Larger Than A Man\u2019s Hand!\u201d I\nWe are indebted to the Associated Press\nfor the above photograph. It was taken in\nBuffalo. The office of the State Division of\nPlacement and Unemployment was jammed\nwith hundreds of war workers, laid off as a\nresult of cutbacks in government airplane\ncontracts. It was necessary to call in the\npolice to help direct the crowd. All were\nseeking unemployment benefits.\n\u201cJust a cloud no larger than a man\u2019s\nhand,\u201d but it gives warning of the coming\nstorm. It\u2019s comparatively easy to handle the\nunemployment1 problem now, but how about\na month from now, or six months from now?\nCongress should not wait until the storm\nis upon us. It should pass the Murray Full\nEmployment Bill. It should follow the advice\nof President Truman and enact adequate un\nemployment benefits NOW and save a danger\nous situation.\nNothing can be lost by that, for, if the\nstorm doesn\u2019t come, it won\u2019t be necessary to\nuse the Murray Act or unemployment bene\nfits, but if the storm comes, and we haven\u2019t\nthis protection, our country may face a\nserious disaster. REMEMBER WHAT HAP\nPENED AFTER THE CRASH OF \u201929!\nTrades Hear Plea\nTo End Disputes\nOn Jurisdictions\nNew York Told WPB May\nEnd Building Restrictions\nBy December\nNEW YORK\u2014Abolition of juris\ndictional disputes through volun\ntary agreement by the building and\nconstruction trades was urged last\nweek by President Thomas A. Mur\nray of the New York State Fed\neration of Labor at a conference of\nrepresentatives from 30 Building\nand Construction Trades Councils\nin various parts of the State.\nMurray chaired the one-day con\nference, which Was arranged by the\nNew York Building and Construction\nTrades Council \u2019to consider postwar\nproblems of the industry and the es\ntablishment of a state-wide organiza\ntion of the trades.\nPresident Howard McSpedon of\nthe New York Council, revealed to\nthe delegates that War Production\nBoard Chief J. A. Krug had told\nhim that all war-time restrictions\non construction work might be\nlifted by December or January.\nMcSpedon also revealed that\nonly 7,000 building trades me\nchanics are now working at their\n(Continued on Page Two)\nRenewal Sought Of\nNorwalk Agreement\nWith the agreement between the\nInternational Ladies Garment Work\ners Union and the Rabhor Co., South\nNorwalk, expiring on July 31, nego\ntiations for the renewal of the con\ntract are now being made.\nOn June 29 the I.L.G.W.U. received\na communication from the Rabhor\nmanagement which stated \u201cIn accord\nance with the provision of the\nagreement made on Aug. 5, 1943, by\nand between the undersigned and your\nlocal, we hereby give you notice that\nit is our desire to terminate this\nagreement on Aug. 4, 1945.\u201d\nOn July 9, Vice-President Harry\nWander, EOT director, sent the fol\nlowing reply to the company:\n\u201cI wish to inform you that the\nmembers of our union employed by\nyour company have chosen our union\nas their sole collective bargaining\nagency and I therefore request your\ncompany to meet with us at your\nearliest convenience for the purpose of\nnegotiating a new agreement.\u201d\nAFL Rejoices At\nBritish Election\nNEW YORK\u2014(FP)\u2014It was like the day after Nov. 7,\n1944, all over again as U. S. workers joined the rejoicing of\nthe British people at the election'victory of the British Labor\nparty, which campaigned on a platform of jobs and security.\nAFL President William Green keynoted the reaction of Ameri\ncan labor to the news in Washington when he said the landslide vote\n\u201cshould not be viewed as a repudiation of the brilliant war leader\nship of Winston Churchill but rather as a popular rejection of the\nstandpat domestic policies of the Conservative party.\u201d\nWE WANT IT TOO\n\u201cThe Labor party victory,\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cmust be interpreted as the\noutcome of the insistent demand\nof British workers to gain higher\nliving standards and a greater de\ngree of economic an<$ social secur\nity. The same aspiration for a\nbetter life after the grim experi\nences of war are moving workers in\nour own country.\u201d\nNews of the election returns sent\nViscount Halifax, British ambassador\nto the U>S., scurrying home to Lon\ndon where he was expected to be re\nplaced almost immediately. Halifax\u2019s\nclose association with the Neville\nChamberlain appeasement policies has\nnot made him well-liked among\nAmerican workers.\nThe clearcut socialist victory\nshowed the disgust of the British\npeople with the campaign tactics\nused by the Conservatives who\ntried to evade the real bread\nand-butter needs of the people by\ntalking of the red menace. Chur\nchill set the tone when he charged\nthe Labor party would introduce\n\u201cGestapo controls\u201d into Britain if\nelected. Eden accused the Labor\nparty, which had strongly cam\n(Continued on Page Three)\nNothing Sweet In\nCo.\u2019s Labor Policies\nSPRECKLES, Calif.\u2014A sweet\ntime is in store for the regional War\nLabor Board in the dispute case of\nthe United Sugar Workers Council\n(AFL) of California.\nFour big sugar companies are in\nvolved on the other side\u2014Spreckels,\nAmerican Crystal, Holly and Union.\nAt issue are hours, overtime, holi\ndays, sick leave, checkoff and premium\npay. At the Union firm there is an\nadditional issue of wage differentials.\nThe council has locals in .Spreckels\nand a number of other California\nsugar beet processing centers. Mem\nbership is about 3,000. First step was\nto be recommendations to the WLB\nafter dispute hearings by a tripartite\npanel.\nState Anti-Union\nLaw No Barrier\nTo A Union Shop\nW.L.B. Says Federal Law\nTakes Precedence Over\nState Legislation\nWASHINGTON\u2014 (FP)_In a de\ncision of wide importance, the Natl.\nWar Labor Board said the War La\nbor Disputes act is superior to any\nstate constitution or statute that\nwould deny establishment of main\ntenance of union membership\nclauses in a contract.\nActing on a petition from the attor\nney general of Florida, who asked to\nintervene because of an amendment to\nthat state\u2019s constitution adopted last\nNovember, the WLB denied the pe\ntition with industry members dissent\ning.\nThe Florida constitutional amend\nment says \u201cthe right of persons to\nwork shall not be denied or abridged\non account of membership or non\nmembership in any labor union or\nlabor organization; provided, that this\nclause shall not be construed to deny\nor abridge the right of employes by\nor through a labor organization or\nlabor union to bargain collectively\nwith their employer.\u201d\nInvolved in the case are the St.\nJoe Paper Co., Port St. Joe, Fla.,\nand three AFL unions; the Inti.\nBro. of Papermakers; Inti. Bro. of\nElectrical Workers and the Inti.\nAssn, of Machinists. The WLB had\ngranted the usual voluntary main\ntenance of membership clause to\nthe 450 workers\nDANGER HOURS\nThe National Safety Council re\nports that the hours between 6 and\n8 p.m. are the most dangerous traffic\nhours for drivers and pedestrians.\nAct Proposes\n75c Minimum,\n35-Hour Week\nRep. Patterson of California\nWould Amend Wage\nAnd Hour Law\nWASHINGTON (FP) One of\nthe new California liberals, Rep. El\nlis Patterson (D., Cal.), has intro\nduced a bill calling for amendent of\nthe federal wage and hours law to\nprovide a 75c minimum wage and a\n35 hour week.\nThe bill, HR 3719, broadens the\ndefinition of \u201ccommerce\u201d to in\nclude all employers engaged in\ntrade, traffic, commerce, transpor\ntation or communication among the\nseveral states so as to cover thou\nsands now barred from federal la\nbor laws.\nPatterson\u2019s bill would prohibit child\nlabor and bars the inclusion of tips,\nboard, lodging or other facilities cus\ntomarily furnished, in figuring wages.\nIt calls for payment of time and a\nhalf after 35 hours unless by contract\nor NLRB order an agreement has\nbeen reached for employment of up\nto 1,000 hours in any 26 week period\nor 2,000 hours for 52 weeks.\nTo attain the 75c minimum\n(Continued on Page Two)\nBuilding Trades\nD4N TRACY,\nAssistant Secretary of Labor, and\nco-chairman of the Wage Adjust\nment Board, who told The Union\nTimes that paid vacations for\nbuilding tradesmen are \u201cin\nevitable.\u201d\nSenators Warn\nNation Must Be\nReady For Peace\n_\nAssert People Will Not\nStand For Another Post\nWar Depression\nW ASHINGTON\u2014\u2014Economic\nupheavals following World\nWar I, the recent landslide in\nfavor of the Labor party at\nthe British polls and the de\nmands of peace and security\nwere cited this week in argu\nments before the Senate Bank\ning and Currency Committee\nfor the \u201cfull employment\nbill,\u201d under which the Gov\nernment would provide work\nif private enterprise failed to\nmeet the estimates of a na\ntional job budget.\nThe witnesses were sponsors of\nthe measure, which was introduced\nin January. Having seen no\nchance of Congressional decision\non the bill before the summer re\ncess, they arranged two days of\nhearings to lay the groundwork for\nmore comprehensive hearings in\nthe fall, when veterans, business\nmen, representatives of agriculture,\nof labor, of State and local govern\nments, of religious organizations\nand of women\u2019s groups will appear.\nThe hearing found the legisla\ntion\u2019s sponsors highly conscious of\nthe defeat of the Churchill Con\nservative Government and losing\nlittle time bringing it into their\narguments.\nWAGNER INTERPRETS POLL\nSenator Robert F. Wagner of New\nYork, committee chairman and a\nsponsor of the bill, said in opening\nthe session that the \u201cwar-weary\npeople of Britain\u201d knew that \u201cecon\nomic tranquility rests upon full em\nployment, with all the social gains\nthat full employment means for all\nthe people.\u201d\n\u201cThey were not convinced,\u201d he\nadded, \u201cthat the Government in\npower was sufficiently resolute in\nits determination to achieve post\nwar full employment\u2014and so they\nhave elected another Government\nwhich is pledged to that purpose.\u201d\nNo one who knew the history\nof all the English-speaking peoples,\nhe declared, would put any stock in\nthe contention raised in some quar\nters that the election meant \u201ca\nswing away from democracy.\u201d\nSenator James E. Murray of Mon\ntana, chairman of the Committee on\nEducation and Labor, who introduced\nthe bill, asserted that the people of\nBritain \u201cseem to have turned toward\nsocialism as a possible solution of\ntheir problems of domestic recon\nstruction.\u201d\n\u201cIn the days to come,\u201d he con\ntinued, \u201cI can see nothing but con\nflict and recrimination for capitalism\nin America unless we provide a pro\ngram which will insure employment\nfor all Americans who are able and\nwilling to work.\u201d\nPOINTS TO TRUMAN VIEWS\nHe recalled that in December, with\nPresident Truman, then a Senator,\nhe reported to the Military Affairs\nCommittee that \u201cunless an economic\nsubstitute is found for war contracts,\nmass unemployment will become a\nserious threat and the number of un\nemployed men and women in this\ncountry might easily surpass anything\nthat was dreamed of during the last\ndepression.\u201d\nThe pending measure, he added,\nwas patterned after phases of the\nlate President Roosevelt\u2019s \u201ceco\nnomic bill of rights,\u201d embodied in\nhis message to Congress in Janu\nary, 1944, which set the \u201cfull em\nployment\u201d goal at 60,000,000 jobs.\nSenator Joseph C. O\u2019Mahoney of\nWyoming, a third sponsor of the bill,\ntold the committee that unemployment\nbetween 1929 and 1941 had cost\n$365,000,000,000 in business sales,\nmore than the cost of the war; $69,\n000,000,000 in corporate profits losses,\na $37,000,000,000 loss of net income\nfor non-farm proprietors, one of $24,\n000,000,000 in the net income of farm\noperators and a loss of $175,000,000,\n000 in the potential incomes of wage\nand-salary workers.\n\u201cThe most frightening thing\nabout the depression which fol\nlowed World War I,\u201d he said, .\u201cis\nthat it was eradicted only by World\nWar II.\u201d\nHe called the pending legislation\n\u201ca bill for economic preparedness.\u2019*\nThe bill was presented as a pro\ngram but not necessarily a rigid\nblueprint, and on this basis has\nbipartisan support.\n(Continued on Page Three)","height":"26793","width":"20745"}}
